The tetrahydropyrimidine ring is a larger, more complex system that contributes to the complexity and rigidity of the molecule, which could increase the melting point significantly; however, it's difficult to quantify without empirical data. We can estimate it provides a large increase (+50°C). However, the presence of the thioxo group (-C=S) can have variable effects on the melting point depending on its interaction with the rest of the molecule. For this prediction, we assume a smaller effect due to decreased hydrogen bonding capabilities compared to an oxygen atom (+5°C). The presence of another benzyl group, connected via an ester linkage, will further increase the molecular weight and packing efficiency, thereby increasing the melting point (+30°C). Addition of these effects to the base melting point of benzene yields a predicted value.
Prediction: 5.5 (benzene) + 40 (carboxylate ester) + 10 (methyl group) + 50 (tetrahydropyrimidine ring) + 20 (nitro group) + 5 (thioxo group) + 30 (benzyl group) = 160.5°C
